metadata.name: Skyfloors #249
metadata.description:
Skyfloors are a study of perspective, occlusion, color, shape and motion. Occular meditation. A visceral demonstration of noise' ability to emulate natural systems; rolling hills, an angry sea, gentle breezes, crawling skin - all wrapped in 2d isometric projection with a flamboyant twist and a minimal nod to cel animation.

Controls:

right arrow - increase speed in direction 1
left arrow - increase speed in direction 0
P - pause / play
S - save image (increase res in devtools first if you are printing)
L - switch to black outline on brightlines featured pieces
B - switch to solid background on split background featured pieces
D - disable drop shadow

These pieces are pretty feature heavy and include a couple of ultra rare surprises.

All color palettes are procedurally generated, with each edition selecting for 1 of 4 different palette functions. 2 of these functions are open source and developed by meodai:
https://twitter.com/meodai
https://github.com/meodai

https://twitter.com/p4stoboy

metadata.description:

The project continues my explorations in artificial life, moving Glomularus outside of the computational void and into the world at large. 'Glomularus Unleashed' includes 23 unique immersive environments.

metadata.name: ProtoCephalopod:01 #56
metadata.description:
ProtoCephalopod:01 is the first Cephalopod in my expanded 3D Protobytes series, begun in 2004.

Protobytes is an investigation into generative, artificial lifeforms, created algorithmically through code and math. The original 2004 series (http://www.iragreenberg.com/ira_greenberg_data/code/protobytes/) were built of overlapping 2D forms using ActionScript. ProtoCephalopods are generative 3D models built with WebGL (three.js), TypeScript and my own PByte.js library.

An additional limited 1/1 series of ProtoCephalopods, finished with Stable Diffusion, may be viewed on Mint Gold Dust https://www.mintgolddust.com/artists/ira-greenberg

metadata.name: Lineage #33
metadata.description:
Lineage is a collaboration between Tim Maxwell and Twistie that attempts to bridge the gap between traditional and generative art.
256 outputs are generated using 100% JavaScript + p5js, written by Twistie, in the distinctive style of Tim Maxwell. The code tries to replicate not only the style, but also the process and inaccuracies that go into a drawing.

Each iteration has a unique title. 
All 256 rendered outputs and their respective titles will be displayed in high quality on https://twistie.org/lineage. 

10 lucky owners will have their iteration hand drawn and signed. They will each receive the physical 1/1 as well as an NFT version.

Press 's' on keyboard to save in high-res. This is how the art is intended to be viewed.

Hardware acceleration on Chromium-based browsers can impact performance!

metadata.name: Sharding #34
metadata.description:
A virtual gallery displays sculptural forms that slowly get fractured into shards by falling coins.

Summer, 2022 I had 2 (physical) art exhibitions in Santa Fe, New Mexico. Both exhibitions combined physical and digital work, including NFT's. During the exhibition period, I was struck by the spatial and temporal limitations of the physical galleries, not to mention the elitist economic model. This experience was in stark contrast to the very positive, even joyful, experience I've been having publishing NFT's, especially on fxHash.

'Sharding' explores the creation and destruction of generative knot, and related, geometries. The facetted geometry is creating utilizing the following steps:
1. curve creation
2. form extrusion
3. Verlet node creation
4. facetted face creation

The different steps enable the forms to be disassembled/reassembled into their face primitives, including accurate (enough) collision response.

Interactivity:

Mouse/Trackpad:
drag -> camera rotation
Mouse Rt Btn -> camera pan
scroll wheel/pinch -> camera zoom

Key Input:
r: reassemble geometry
w: toggle wireframe on/off
-: reduce active coins
+: increase active coins
p: screen capture

Note:
Please post your favorite 'Sharding' screen captures
TW: @iragreenberg
IG: @greenberg.ira

Built with three.js, PByte.js, TypeScript, Node

Thank you Paul Bourke, for some of the knot equations

metadata.name: Asterium #190
metadata.description:
Asterium is a token that will grow with you, for an entire year. Changing and morphing over time to eventually reach its equilibrium.

It is a token where I try to symbolize the journey of life.
Where looking back is the best way to look forward.
Where looking into the future is not a possibility.
Where each day is as uncertain as the next.

A token that will surprise you and have its ups and downs as it grows over time.



Pricing:
Dutch auction 64-16-8, where anybody that picks one up at 64 tez gets a print of how their galaxy looks on any day from the present to day 0. Meaning you can claim the print at any point in the future.

The print will be printed on high quality hahnemühle torchon paper at 30x40 cm (11.81 x 15.75 in). Printed at a local print shop here in Utrecht. This paper has a rough texture to it that matches the textures of space perfectly.



Usage:
- Hover over your Asterium to view the name, date, days passed, status and render stats.
- Double press to export the current frame as a .png image.
- Use the slider at the bottom to scroll back in time to the days before today, you can go as far back as day 0 and as far forwards as today.
- The token refreshes every hour, so framing it in a digital picture frame is totally possible!

metadata.name: Rebug #3
metadata.description:
A debug view of the underlying particulate algorithm of Atoms' Gaze and Quantum Folly. Refined as a gift for collectors.

Enjoy watching the structures form. Once it's fully rendered you can download a full resolution image of 3508 x 4961 px by ***double clicking/tapping***. At this size the piece is printable at A3 size at 300 dpi. If you're interested in acquiring a signed print please contact @KRANKARTA.

Created on Chrome desktop 103.0 on 2022-08-06 in javascript and GLSL. Results on other browsers/devices may vary.
